{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511842"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:46:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:46:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11804"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11804"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.67,0.05,0.07,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4409"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115457"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4409"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97460"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1914"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6256"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26950"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49102"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115457"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man with chronic liver disease presents to the Emergency Department feeling generally unwell. He has had some chills and mild abdominal pain for the last few days. On examination his blood pressure is 143/96 mmHg, pulse 82 min, respiratory rate 18/min, oxygen saturation 97% on room air and temperature 38.2 Celsius. He has mild diffuse abdominal tenderness and moderate ascites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA diagnostic paracentesis is performed and sent for microscopy gram stain, cell count and cultures. The neutrophil count of the ascitic fluid is 0.37 x 10^9/L (normal: \u0026lt;0.25 x 10\u2079/L), but the gram stain and cultures are not back yet.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Furosemide","Ceftriaxone","Salt restriction","Spironolactone","Total paracentesis with albumin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP) as indicated by the clinical findings and the presence of ascites; with a neutrophil count over 0.25 x 10^9/L in the ascitic fluid. This requires immediate antibiotics, \u003Cstrong\u003Eceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E being the recommended option. An appropriate dose to start with is 2g IV daily and this should be continued for at least 5-7 days. This covers \u003Cem\u003EE. coli, Klebsiella \u003C/em\u003Eand \u003Cem\u003EStreptococci\u003C/em\u003E, which are the most common causes of SBP. In addition, albumin 1.5g/kg day 1 and 1g/kg day 3 would be given to reduce the risk of HRS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E would be part of the long term management of ascites and would be added following treatment with an anti-mineralocorticoid such as spironolactone.\u003Cstrong\u003ESalt restriction \u003C/strong\u003Eis  not correct, but this is part of the long term management of ascites and would not be appropriate as an initial management strategy for SBP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E is a first line medication for treating ascites, however this patient\u0027s primary issue is SBP, not the ascites itself. Therefore, it would be appropriate to consider prescribing this during the patients stay or following resolution of the SBP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is limited evidence to support performing a \u003Cstrong\u003Etotal paracentesis\u003C/strong\u003E in patients with SBP.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ceftriaxone is the antibiotic of choice for treating spontaneous bacterial peritonitis.","Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis is diagnosed when the neutrophil count in ascitic fluid is greater than 0.25 x 10^9/L.","Immediate antibiotic treatment is crucial in spontaneous bacterial peritonitis to prevent complications."],"references":["European Association for the Study of the Liver. EASL Clinical Practice Guidelines for the management of patients with decompensated cirrhosis. J Hepatol. 2018 Aug;69(2):406-460. doi: 10.1016/j.jhep.2018.03.024. Epub 2018 Apr 10. Erratum in: J Hepatol. 2018 Nov;69(5):1207. doi: 10.1016/j.jhep.2018.08.009. PMID: 29653741. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29653741/","Iogna Prat L, Wilson P, Freeman SC, Sutton AJ, Cooper NJ, Roccarina D, Benmassaoud A, Plaz Torres MC, Hawkins N, Cowlin M, Milne EJ, Thorburn D, Pavlov CS, Davidson BR, Tsochatzis E, Gurusamy KS. Antibiotic treatment for spontaneous bacterial peritonitis in people with decompensated liver cirrhosis: a network meta-analysis. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2019 Sep 16;9(9):CD013120. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD013120.pub2. PMID: 31524949; PMCID: PMC6746213. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6746213/","Yim HJ, Kim TH, Suh SJ, Yim SY, Jung YK, Seo YS, Kang SH, Kim MY, Baik SK, Kim HS, Kim YS, Park SY, Kim BI, Park JY, Heo J, Sohn JH, Heo NY, Han KH, Um SH. Response-Guided Therapy With Cefotaxime, Ceftriaxone, or Ciprofloxacin for Spontaneous Bacterial Peritonitis: A Randomized Trial: A Validation Study of 2021 AASLD Practice Guidance for SBP. Am J Gastroenterol. 2023 Apr 1;118(4):654-663. doi: 10.14309/ajg.0000000000002126. Epub 2023 Jan 3. PMID: 36594820. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36594820/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97460"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11804"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97460"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T19:57:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T19:58:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4409"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115457"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,